{{Refimprove|date=September 2014}} [[Image:1100 siluroBandini.jpg|250px|right|thumb|[[Ilario Bandini]] at [[Perugia]] in 1950]] [[Image:Bandini1100siluroh.jpg|250px|right|thumb]] [[Image:Bandini1100siluro.jpg|200px|right|thumb|The start of the 1949 Mille Miglia]] [[Image:Bandini a pescara.jpg|250px|right|thumb|Ilario Bandini at [[Pescara]], with his brother Gualtiero behind him.]] [[Image:Bandini1100siluroE.JPG|250px|right|thumb|Torpedo in a recent event]] [[Image:SiluroBandini.JPG|250px|right|thumb|1100 Torpedo on Bandini Day]] [[Image:Bandini1100A.JPG|250px|right|thumb|Passenger compartment and [[dashboard]].]] The '''Bandini 1100 Siluro''' is a racing car produced from 1947 to 1949 by [[Bandini Automobili]] in [[Forlì]], Italy.
The 1100 Siluro was the first Bandini model created expressly for racing. The style and materials were selected for speed, performance and weight-savings. The name Siluro ({{lang-en|torpedo}}) was chosen to acknowledge the aerodynamic shape and was thought to be a good omen for the races. Initially, to reduce weight and simplify repairs, they were not even painted.
The 1100 Siluro first participated in competitions in 1949. These included Italian competitions such as the "Giro dell'Umbria" (Lap of [[Umbria]]), the "Pescara Circuit", and the "Senigallia Circuit", as well as more important, internationally recognized events, such as [[Mille Miglia]]. It was driven by Richard W. Gent at [[Watkins Glen International|Watkins Glen]] in the 1951 Grand Prix,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.conceptcarz.com/vehicle/z9615/Bandini-Siluro.aspx|publisher=Conceptcarz.com|title=1947 Bandini Siluro news, pictures, specifications, and information|accessdate=31 May 2014}}</ref> introducing the cars to the auto-sports fans of the United States.
==The body== The body had two seats and was made of aluminium. It was built at the Bandini headquarters in Via Cesare Battisti in [[Forlì]]. Small motor-cycle style wheel-guards were fitted, allowing them to remain separate from the body. The overall result is a combination of technology and aerodynamically efficient ''torpedo'' styling, as well as being described as having elements from the animal kingdom. Ilario Bandini loved to reiterate that nature had solved very well functional problems that man is only beginning to face. Thus, he said, the [[Grille (motor vehicle)|grille]], designed to direct as much air to the engine without overloading the front section, has the characteristics of enormous nostrils; lights are encased in it as the eyes of a [[fish]], the heat is disposed of using [[louver]]s resembling the gills of a [[shark]]. In order to reduce weight as much as possible, the tail was very short and round and only the passenger had a door.
==The chassis== The frame, a refinement of the [[Bandini 1100|1100 sport]] frame, is the version developed for competition. The size and weight are reduced significantly. The height from the ground is {{convert|13|cm|0|abbr=on}}, while the bare chassis weighs only {{convert|25|kg|lb|0|abbr=on}}.{{Citation needed|date=November 2009}}
* Structure and material: frame of elliptical section tubes, aviation grade [[steel]] * [[Suspension (mechanical)|Suspension]]: ** Front: Independent, triangles overlapping with [[Shock absorber|shock]] hydraulic telescopic tilted and [[Spring (device)|springs]] cylindrical helical coaxial ** Rear: a bridge with two rigid leaf spring semiellittiche inclined * [[Brake|Braking system]]: ** Service: hydraulics, drum front and rear ** Parking Mechanical tape, on [[Transmission (mechanics)|transmission]] * [[Steering]]: worm drive * Wheels: [[Borrani]] Ray * [[Tank]]: {{Convert|50|L|usgal impgal|0|abbr=on}} * [[Transmission (mechanics)|Transmission]]: transmission shaft with central rear [[differential (mechanical device)|differential]] and halfshaft
==The engine== The chassis, designed to accommodate modified [[Fiat 1100 (1937)|Fiat 1100]] engines, proved suitable for different engines up to 1500 cc [[engine capacity]].
===1100 DOHC version === * Positioning: forward longitudinal, 4-cylinder in-line * [[Engine displacement|Displacement]]: 1089 cc * [[Bore (engine)|Bore]] and [[Stroke (engine)|Stroke]]: 68&nbsp;mm x 75&nbsp;mm * [[Cylinder head|Head]]: Derived Alfa Romeo 6 adapted to the 4-cylinder engine, 2 inclined valves per cylinder, 2 camshafts controlled by chain and gears * [[Power (physics)|Power]] maximum: {{convert|65|hp|abbr=on}} * Fuel system: 2 carburettors * Lubricate: wet sump with pump gear and vertical cooler on the front * Cooling: forced liquid with [[centrifugal pump]] and cooler on the front * [[Gearbox]] and clutch: 4 speed+ RG, clutch single dry disc * Ignition and electrical system: coil and [[distributor]] battery 12 [[volt|V]] and [[Electrical generator|generator]]
===Fiat-Siata 1500 version === * Positioning: forward longitudinal, 4-cylinder in-line * [[Engine displacement|Displacement]]: 1496 cc * [[Power (physics)|Power]] maximum: 90 [[Horsepower|hp]] 6000 [[rpm]] * Fuel system: 2 carburettors * Lubrication: wet sump with pump gear and vertical cooler on the front * Cooling: forced liquid with centrifugal pump and cooler on the front * [[Gearbox]] and clutch: 4 speed + RG, clutch single dry disc * Ignition and electrical equipment: coil and [[distributor]], battery 12 [[volt|V]] and [[Electrical generator|generator]] *[[Weight]] total: {{convert|485|kg|lb|0|abbr=on}}
